## Optional libraries (when adding data-heavy features)

Use **only when the product needs them** — they are not defaults for this marketing codebase:

| Concern | Examples |
|---|---|
| Server/async client state | TanStack Query, SWR |
| Component primitives | shadcn/ui, Radix |
| Forms | react-hook-form + zod |
| Charts | Recharts or similar |

---

## Structure (App Router)

- **`app/<segment>/page.tsx|jsx|js`** — route UI
- **`app/<segment>/layout.tsx|jsx|js`** — shared shell for a subtree
- **`app/api/<segment>/route.ts|js`** — HTTP handlers
- Colocate small modules next to their route or under `app/components/` if that is the project pattern

### Component discipline

- Prefer passing data as props from Server Components down to client leaves when possible
- Avoid huge files — split sections/components when a page grows
- Fetch from handlers or external APIs in one place; avoid scattering `fetch` without a clear convention

---

## TypeScript (when used)

- Prefer `strict` typings for new TS modules
- Avoid `any` — use `unknown` and narrow, or explicit types for API JSON
- Do not mirror legacy "Go struct" language unless the repo actually shares a Go API

---

## Performance & UX

- Use `next/image` where appropriate for optimized images
- Lazy-load heavy client-only sections if they hurt initial load
- Meaningful loading and error UI for async boundaries when users depend on the result

---

## Do Not

- Do not assume Create React App or Vite-only SPA routing — routes are file-system based under `app/`
- Do not add `"use client"` to entire trees without need — keep server boundaries wide
- Do not ship secrets to the client — environment variables for server/handlers only (`NEXT_PUBLIC_*` only for truly public values)
